\begin_layout Plain Layout
Given a pure state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Phi}$
\end_inset

, when we measure an observable represented by an Hermitian matrix
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}$
\end_inset

, the measurement result is one of the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}$
\end_inset

.
 The probability of getting a particular eigenvalue
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\melem{\Phi}{P}{\Phi}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is the projection operator onto the eigenspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 This rule of computing the probability is called the Born rule 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Born1983,Mermin2007,Jaeger2007"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, which is used when we want to extract information from a quantum computer.
 For any mixed state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, the generalized Born rule induces a conventional quantum probability measure
 
\begin_inset Formula $\muB_{\rho}:\events\rightarrow[0,1]$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

 is the set of all projection operators on a given Hilbert space.
 Conversely, any quantum probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:\events\rightarrow[0,1]$
\end_inset

 can be induced from a mixed state 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 in the Hilbert space of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $D\ge3$
\end_inset

 according to Gleason's theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gleason1957,Redhead1987-REDINA,peres1995quantum,RichmanBridges1999,Hamhalter2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In another word, this state 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is the unique state consistent with any given quantum probability measure.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\emph on
probability space
\emph default
 is a mathematical abstraction specifying the necessary conditions for reasoning
 coherently about collections of uncertain events 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kolmogorov1950,544199,Griffiths2003,Grabisch2016"
posttextlist "Kolmogorov1950"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In the quantum case, the events of interest are specified by 
\emph on
projection operators
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 satisfying the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{2}=P$
\end_inset

.
 These include the empty projector
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{0}$
\end_inset

, the identity projector
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{1}$
\end_inset

, projectors of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{\Phi}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Phi}$
\end_inset

 is a pure quantum state (an element of a Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

), sums of 
\emph on
orthogonal
\emph default
 projectors
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}P_{1}=\mathbb{0}$
\end_inset

, and products of 
\emph on
commuting
\emph default
 projectors 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}P_{1}=P_{1}P_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 In a quantum probability space 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "10.2307/2308516,gleason1957,Redhead1987-REDINA,Maassen2010,Abramsky2012"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, each event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}$
\end_inset

 is mapped to a probability
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(P_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 using a probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:\events\rightarrow\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

 is the set of all events, (i.e., projectors on a given Hilbert space), subject
 to the following constraints: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\mathbb{0}\right)=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\mathbb{1}\right)=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\mathbb{1}-P\right)=1-\mu\left(P\right)$
\end_inset

, and for each pair of 
\emph on
orthogonal
\emph default
 projectors 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu\left(P_{0}+P_{1}\right)=\mu\left(P_{0}\right)+\mu\left(P_{1}\right)\,.\label{eq:QuantumProbability-Addition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Given a Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 and a probability assignment for every projector 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, we can define the expectation value of an observable
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}$
\end_inset

 having spectral decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}=\sum_{i=1}^{D}\lambda_{i}P_{i}$
\end_inset

, with eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "544199,Jaeger2007"
literal "true"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\expval{\mathbf{O}}_{\mu}=\sum_{i=1}^{D}\lambda_{i}\mu\left(P_{i}\right)\,,\label{eq:quantum-expectation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 might be omitted if it is clear according to the context.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A conventional quantum probability measure can easily be constructed using
 the Born rule if one knows the current pure unnormalized quantum state
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Phi}\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

; then the Born rule induces a probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\muB_{\Phi}$
\end_inset

 defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\muB_{\Phi}(P)=\frac{\melem{\Phi}{P}{\Phi}}{\ip{\Phi}{\Phi}}\,.\label{eq:Born}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Phi}$
\end_inset

 is normalized, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Born"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) could be simplified as 
\begin_inset Formula $\muB_{\Phi}(P)=\melem{\Phi}{P}{\Phi}$
\end_inset

.
 For mixed states 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\sum_{j=1}^{N}q_{j}\proj{\Phi_{j}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Phi_{j}}\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

