\begin_layout Standard
The final issue that must be addressed in the discrete theory put forward
 in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "discretequantumtheoryIIa"

\end_inset

 concerns measurement.
 To recap, within the theory, states are 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-dimensional vectors with complex discrete-valued amplitudes drawn from
 a totally-ordered range, 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{D}(k)$
\end_inset

, in the underlying finite field.
 These states possess, by construction, having field norms in the non-negative
 integers, all in the ordered range of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:region"

\end_inset

, and hence potentially produce probabilities that can be ordered.
 Our point is that, although the mathematical framework of conventional
 quantum mechanics relies on infinite precision probabilities, it is impossible
 in practice to measure exact equality of real numbers — we can only achieve
 an approximation within measurement accuracy.
 Significantly, when we use finite fields, this measurement accuracy will
 be encoded in the size of the finite field used for measurements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-dimensional Hilbert space in conventional quantum theory, although we can
 measure the probability for every eigenprojector of an observable as discussed
 in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:fuzzy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, our previous quantum circuits in Figures
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:alg"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Quantum-Circuit-Deutsch"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:dbsearch"

\end_inset

 always measure in the computational basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{0},\ldots,\ket{i},\ldots,\ket{D-1}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, it is sufficient to only consider measuring in the computational
 basis because measuring in another basis is the same as applying a quantum
 gate and measuring in the computational basis.
 In this situation, the Born rule for pure states, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Born"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), can be simplified as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\muB_{\Psi}\left(\proj{i}\right)\equiv\muB_{\Psi}\left(i\right)=\frac{\ip{\Psi}{i}\ip{i}{\Psi}}{\ip{\Psi}{\Psi}}=\frac{\left|\ip{i}{\Psi}\right|^{2}}{\ip{\Psi}{\Psi}}=\frac{\left|\alpha_{i}\right|^{2}}{\ip{\Psi}{\Psi}}\,,\label{eq:Born-ComputationalBasis}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}=\begin{pmatrix}\alpha_{0} & \alpha_{1} & \ldots & \alpha_{D-1}\end{pmatrix}^{T}$
\end_inset

 is an unnormalized state.
 Hereafter, we will simplify by calling 
\begin_inset Formula $\muB_{\Psi}\left(i\right)$
\end_inset

